While modernization and urbanization have shifted perspectives—making it increasingly common to see divorce as a legal and personal necessity in cases of irreconcilable differences, abuse, or the total breakdown of a relationship—there remains a strong cultural preference for conflict resolution and stability. Divorce is generally not celebrated or viewed as a trivial matter; it is often treated with a sense of gravity or regret due to the impact it has on the broader family structure. Consequently, the cultural stance tends to be cautious, acknowledging the necessity of divorce in extreme or failed circumstances, but generally favoring the endurance of the marital bond.

